export const caseStudySummaries = "## Wealth Lens: AI-Powered Investment Manager\n**Company:** Personal Project | **Year:** 2025 | **Role:** Product Designer\n**Tags:** Fintech, AI, Investment, Product Design\n**Outcome:** Designing a unified asset management experience where users track portfolios, get AI-driven investment suggestions, and visualize growth over time.\n\n ## TL;DR Most investors juggle 4–6 apps to track their money — one for stocks, one for mutual funds, a spreadsheet for real estate, a DeFi wallet for crypto. **Wealth Lens** brings everything into a single dashboard where users can add all their assets, track investment history and growth, and receive AI-suggested investment recommendations based on their goals, risk appetite, and market conditions. **Problem:** Fragmented investment tracking leads to poor financial decisions and missed opportunities **Scope:** Mobile-first responsive web app — consumer fintech --- ## Context India's retail investor base has exploded — from 40M demat accounts in 2020 to over 150M in 2025. Yet most of these investors are first-generation, managing portfolios across multiple brokers (Zerodha, Groww, Angel One), mutual fund platforms (Coin, Kuvera), crypto exchanges (WazirX, CoinSwitch), and offline assets like real estate and gold. The result: nobody has a complete picture of their wealth. Decisions are made in silos — selling mutual funds while ignoring underperforming stocks, or over-allocating to crypto without seeing total equity exposure. Existing tools either focus on one asset class or require tedious manual entry. > **The core question:** How do you give everyday investors a single, intelligent view of everything they own — and help them make better decisions without requiring a finance degree? --- ## Defining the Problem I interviewed 15 retail investors (age 24–40, portfolio size ₹2L–₹50L) across experience levels. The findings were consistent: ### Key Pain Points - **No single source of truth** — Investors check 3–5 apps daily. Nobody knows their actual net worth at any given moment. - **Growth tracking is manual** — Users screenshot portfolio values or maintain spreadsheets to track performance over time. Most give up after a few months. - **Decision paralysis** — \"Should I invest more in this fund or diversify?\" Without holistic context, every decision feels like guesswork. - **Jargon overload** — Terms like Sharpe ratio, CAGR, expense ratio, and alpha intimidate new investors. They want simple answers: \"Am I doing well? What should I do next?\" - **No actionable insights** — Apps show data but don't tell you what to do with it. A 12% return sounds good until you realize the benchmark did 18%. ### Research Snapshot | Insight | Source | |---|---| | 13/15 users track investments across 3+ platforms | Interviews | | 80% have no idea of their actual asset allocation | Survey (n=40) | | Average time spent checking investments: 25 min/day | Screen time data | | \"I wish someone would just tell me what to do\" — most common quote | Interviews | | 60% tried portfolio trackers but abandoned within 2 months | Survey | --- ## Design Principles 1. **Consolidate, don't complicate** — Adding an asset should take under 30 seconds. Auto-sync where possible, manual add as fallback. 2. **Insights over information** — Don't just show numbers. Tell the user what the numbers mean and what to do about it. 3. **Progressive intelligence** — Start simple (total value, basic growth). Unlock\n\n---\n\n## Wandr: Collaborative Trip Planning for Groups\n**Company:** Personal Project | **Year:** 2025 | **Role:** Product Designer\n**Tags:** Travel, Collaboration, Product Design\n**Outcome:** Designing a shared itinerary tool that lets groups collaboratively plan multi-city trips — adding stops, commenting on destinations, and coordinating transportation.\n\n ## TL;DR Planning a multi-city vacation with family or friends quickly becomes overwhelming — scattered WhatsApp threads, conflicting spreadsheets, and no single source of truth. I designed **Wandr**, a collaborative trip planning tool where groups can build shared itineraries, add and modify destinations, comment on stops, plan length of stay, and coordinate transportation between locations — all in one place. **Problem:** Group trip planning is fragmented, stressful, and uncoordinated **Scope:** Mobile-first responsive web app — consumer travel UX --- ## Context Every year, millions of group trips fall apart not because people don't want to travel — but because the *planning* breaks down. Coordination across 4–8 people with different preferences, budgets, and schedules is inherently complex. Existing tools either solve for solo travelers (Google Trips, TripIt) or are too generic (shared Google Docs, Notion templates). The gap is clear: there's no purpose-built tool that treats **collaborative group planning** as a first-class experience — where everyone can contribute, discuss, and align on a shared itinerary in real time. > **The core question:** How do you give a group of travelers agency over a shared plan without the experience devolving into chaos? --- ## Defining the Problem I started by interviewing 12 people who had recently planned group trips (3+ travelers, 2+ cities). The patterns were immediately visible: ### Key Pain Points - **No single source of truth** — Plans lived across WhatsApp groups, Google Sheets, screenshots, and individual notes. Nobody knew what was \"final.\" - **Decision paralysis in groups** — Adding a destination meant convincing everyone, but there was no structured way to propose, discuss, or vote on stops. - **Duration planning was guesswork** — Groups rarely aligned on how long to spend at each city. One person wants 3 days in Jaipur, another wants 1. - **Transport between cities was an afterthought** — Flight/train options between stops were researched separately, often by whoever took initiative. - **Uneven contribution** — Usually one person did 80% of the planning work. Others passively consumed the plan. ### User Research Snapshot | Insight | Source | |---|---| | 9/12 users said \"one person ends up doing all the work\" | Interviews | | Average group uses 4+ tools to plan a single trip | Survey (n=30) | | 67% of plans change significantly after initial creation | Survey | | Transport coordination was rated the #1 pain point | Card sort | --- ## Design Principles Before jumping into solutions, I established four principles to guide every decision: 1. **Shared by default** — Every action is visible to the group. No private parallel plans. 2. **Low-friction contribution** — Adding a stop or comment should take < 10 seconds. 3. **Structured flexibility** — Provide enough structure to prevent chaos, but don't over-constrain. Groups need room to explore. 4. **Progressive disclosure** — Show the simple version first (destinations + dates). Transport, budgets, and logistics surface when needed. --- ## Information Architecture The tool is organized around a **Trip** as the top-level container: ``` Trip ├──\n\n---\n\n## Cracking the Code of Offers\n**Company:** JUSPAY | **Year:** 2024 | **Role:** Lead Product Designer\n**Tags:** Fintech, Checkout UX, System Design\n**Outcome:** Redesigning how offers and coupons surface, communicate, and convert on the payment page — across 500+ enterprise merchants and 100M+ daily checkout sessions.\n\n ## TL;DR Offers on Juspay's payment page were broken at every layer — unclear cards, opaque eligibility rules, and scattered discounts. Users couldn't answer the simplest question: *\"What's the best deal I can get right now?\"* I redesigned the entire offers experience — entry points, listing, card design, application flow, and payment nudges — for a system serving 500+ merchants and 100M+ daily sessions. **Problem:** Offers were a frustrating maze instead of a conversion lever **Scope:** Android, iOS, Mobile Web — consumer checkout UX --- ## Context Over the years, offers and coupons have transformed from simple discount codes into strategic instruments. Merchants use them to reinforce brand loyalty, increase average order values, attract fresh customers, and strategically move inventory. Issuers — banks, NBFCs, wallet providers, pay-later services, UPI apps — collaborate with merchants to offer targeted discounts that help them acquire new users and drive platform engagement. Juspay's payment page (HyperCheckout SDK) is highly customizable and renders natively inside merchant apps. This means the offers experience needs to work across wildly different merchant contexts — from quick-commerce (Zepto, BigBasket) to travel (Ixigo) to e-commerce (Meesho) — while staying consistent and intuitive for end users. > **The core tension:** What should be a straightforward bonus for the customer often turns into a frustrating maze. Terms, conditions, and complex interfaces undermine the very goal of these offers. --- ## Defining the Problem When I audited the existing offers experience across multiple merchant integrations, the problems weren't subtle. Offer cards lacked clarity, eligibility rules were opaque, and payment method discounts were scattered. Users couldn't answer the simplest question — *\"What's the best deal I can get right now?\"* ### Key Pain Points - **Lack of clarity in offer selection** — Users struggle to determine which deal provides maximum savings, leading to confusion and suboptimal choices. - **Unclear eligibility explanations** — Users don't understand why certain offers don't apply to their orders, causing frustration and missed opportunities. - **Auto-applied vs. coupon confusion** — Users fail to differentiate between automatically applied discounts and manual coupon codes, often missing better savings. - **Generic offer messaging** — Vague \"Offer Available\" labels lack details, leaving users uncertain about the actual discount value. - **Limited visibility of additional savings** — Users overlook better deals due to poor offer presentation, reducing the effectiveness of promotions. --- ## Understanding Users Research revealed two distinct user archetypes arriving at the payment page with fundamentally different mindsets: ### The Deal Hunter Actively seeks out every possible discount. Will compare offers across payment methods. Won't check out until they're confident they have the best deal. Needs: comprehensive offer visibility, easy comparison, clear eligibility. ### The Straight-to-Pay User Prioritizes speed and simplicity. Already committed to paying — offers aren't top-of-mind, but they'll take a deal if it's effortless. Needs: zero friction, auto-applied savings, no decision paralysis. > **The design constraint:** We need an experience that is seamless, intuitive, and efficient — making offer discovery effortless for Deal Hunters while ensuring a stress-free payment\n\n---\n\n## Mandates: Designing Recurring Payments\n**Company:** JUSPAY | **Year:** 2024 | **Role:** Product Designer II\n**Tags:** Fintech, Recurring Payments, UPI\n**Outcome:** Simplifying recurring payment setup and management — making mandates transparent, trustworthy, and easy to control.\n\n ## TL;DR UPI mandates (autopay) let merchants block or debit recurring amounts from a user's bank account. But the existing flow was confusing — users didn't understand what they were authorizing, how much would be debited, or how to revoke it. I redesigned the mandate creation and confirmation experience across desktop and mobile, making the process transparent, trustworthy, and simple. **Problem:** Users abandoned mandate setup because the flow felt opaque and risky **Scope:** Desktop web, Mobile web, Android & iOS — checkout UX --- ## Context BASBA (Block Amount and Send Back on Approval) is a UPI-based payment flow where the premium amount is blocked via a one-time mandate and only debited after merchant confirmation. This is critical for industries like insurance, subscriptions, and recurring services where the final amount may differ from the initial authorization. The challenge: mandate flows involve multiple parties (merchant, payment aggregator, UPI app, bank) and require users to understand concepts like \"mandate amount vs premium amount\" and \"blocking vs debiting\" — financial concepts most users have never encountered. > **The core tension:** How do you make a complex multi-party financial authorization feel as simple as a regular payment? --- ## Design Showcase <MandatesBento /> --- ## Approach The redesign focused on three principles: 1. **Transparency first** — Show exactly what's being authorized: the premium amount, the mandate ceiling, the end date, and the frequency. No hidden terms. 2. **Progressive disclosure** — Don't overwhelm users with all details upfront. Surface the essentials (amount, app, action) and let curious users dig deeper via \"Know More\" links. 3. **Trust through familiarity** — Use familiar UPI app logos, bank names, and payment patterns so the mandate flow feels like a natural extension of a regular UPI payment. --- ## Key Decisions - **Split-panel desktop layout:** Payment methods on the left, detailed flow on the right — mirrors the mental model of \"choose then configure\" - **QR + UPI ID dual path:** Desktop users get both scan-to-pay and direct UPI ID entry, reducing friction for different user preferences - **Mandate details card:** A clear summary showing Premium Amount, Mandate Amount, End Date, and Frequency — all visible before the user taps \"Proceed to Pay\" - **Multi-app support:** CRED, PhonePe, Google Pay, Paytm, BHIM — users see their preferred app upfront with familiar branding --- ## Impact - Reduced mandate setup abandonment - Improved user trust through transparent amount disclosure - Consistent experience across 500+ merchant integrations ";

